<paragraph blockId="3.[151,635,690,753]" box="[151,340,726,753]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">
<figureCitation box="[151,258,726,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,2000,2024]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,185,1973]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[158,1430,181,1976]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 5–28. Macropsis spp., lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404165/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Figs. 5–7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[269,340,726,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">48–54</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,798,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,798,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Description.</emphasis>
Species with very variable coloration. Brown, greyish brown, or reddish brown, occasionally, with black pattern on head, pro-, and mesonotum (
<figureCitation box="[663,773,834,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,2000,2024]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,185,1973]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[158,1430,181,1976]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 5–28. Macropsis spp., lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4404165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4404165/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Figs. 5–7</figureCitation>
). Most specimens have black frontal spot. In some populations, among females green color form occurs in significant proportion or even prevails.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,798,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">
Male abdominal apodemes of 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[554,570,906,920]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">nd</superScript>
tergite short and comparatively narrow, separated by wide round notch, usually, with truncate tips (
<figureCitation box="[415,553,943,969]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Figs. 48–49</figureCitation>
). Sternal apodemes strongly convergent, separated by narrow notch of variable shape, with truncate or rounded tips (
<figureCitation box="[577,716,978,1005]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Figs. 50–51</figureCitation>
). Penis stem in side view wide, with slight extension in middle (
<figureCitation box="[159,298,1014,1041]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Figs. 52–53</figureCitation>
). 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[330,346,1014,1028]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">nd</superScript>
valvulae of ovipositor usually with 2–3 preapical teeth each (
<figureCitation box="[1038,1122,1014,1041]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–81" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1893,1917]" captionTargetBox="[183,1402,189,1863]" captionTargetId="figure-16@15.[173,1413,181,1869]" captionText="FIGURES 48–81. Macropsis suspecta (48–54), M. vicina (55–61), M. tarbagataica (62–68), and M. iliensis (69–81). 48–49, 55–56, 62–63―male abdominal apodemes of the 2nd tergite; 50–51, 57–58, 64–65, 69, 71—the 2nd sternite; 52–53, 59–60, 66–67, 70, 72, 74, 77, 80―penis, lateral view; 54, 61, 68, 75, 78, 81―the 2nd valvulae of ovipositor; 73, 76, 79―male 2nd abdominal apodemes. 69–70―paratype of M. iliensis; 71–72―paratype of M. tuvensis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4457944" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4457944/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="384">Fig. 54</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
